How This Implements CQRS
Commands (CreateProductCommand, UpdateProductPriceCommand)
→ Modify state via ProductCommandHandler.
Queries (GetProductByIdQuery, GetAllProductsQuery)
→ Read state via ProductQueryHandler.
Separation: No query logic in command handlers and no state mutation in query handlers.
Repository: Simple in-memory store for demo purposes.
✅ Advantages of this approach:

Clear separation of read and write logic.
Easier scaling (e.g., separate read/write databases).
Better maintainability for complex domains.


The Command Query Responsibility Segregation (CQRS) pattern separates
the responsibilities of handling commands (write operations)
and queries (read operations).
This approach improves scalability, maintainability,
and flexibility in applications.
Below is a simple Java implementation of the CQRS pattern.

Benefits:

Scalability: Command and query sides can scale independently.
Optimized Performance: Separate models allow for tailored optimizations.
Maintainability: Clear separation of concerns simplifies the codebase.

Considerations:
Complexity: Requires additional infrastructure for synchronization.
Eventual Consistency: Query models may lag behind the latest state.
